A drop-in service for those who are 18+ and from a black and ethnic minority background. The core element of this Service is for the provision of an action learning project which will research and develop Community Mentoring Services for BME groups across Devon. Where mentoring services are delivered to older people within this Agreement they will be provided as described in D4.1 above; but the core components of this Service are described below. The Service will undertake an exercise to map minority ethnic services and community groups to discover what support mechanisms are in place and where they are located;
Local communities and the statutory sector will be approached to ascertain whether their provision is appropriate;
Where local service provision is not available, or that which is available is not felt to be appropriate, then mentors will set up groups for those individuals who have been identified as meeting the criteria and who wish to be involved;
The Service will endeavour to create new social links and to develop wider social networks for older BME people in the areas of Devon in which the Service is provided;
The Service will develop and populate a database of social opportunities for older BME people in the areas in which the Service operates;
The Service will identify those individuals described within this Agreement who meet the criteria for a mentoring service and will appoint sufficient numbers of Mentors to work with those individuals;
The Service Provider will report periodically throughout the project period of findings of service usage by Black and Minority Ethnic elders, barriers to such usage, and practical and sustainable means of overcoming these;
The Service Provider will undertake a service evaluation at individual and service level which will be conducted according to agreed protocols;
Following this evaluation of the Service and its component parts it will be determined whether the model is suitable and effectively engages with Black and Minority Ethnic Groups;
The Service Provider will assist with the development of a practical Manual or How To guide to inform future Service Providers.
During the term of the Agreement Providers will be expected to consider, and where possible to establish, arrangements to enhance value for money within the provision of the Service. This could include generating efficiencies by partnership working with other providers, services or voluntary sector organisations, the generation of additional resources from other resources which would complement the contracted services or, in the case of not-for-profit organisations, the use of volunteers to complement the role of paid staff.

Mentoring service for those over 45 years and from a bme background, the service offers 1 to 1 support and group activities. The Service is a social contact centre to enable isolated Chinese and Muslim Elders to meet together on culturally specific days. The Service is situated at St Sidwells, Sidwell Street Exeter. The Service will operate on two days per week, one day being exclusively for Chinese Elders (Tuesday) and the second (Thursday) for Muslim Elders. The Service Provider will provide and pay for suitable transport for Service Users from their home to the centre and back. The Service will offer a range of activities during the day. The nature of the activities will be directed by Service Users, and may include (but shall not be limited to):
Visiting healthcare practitioners provided by the PCT e.g. occupational therapy, chiropody;
Advice and information sessions provided by the voluntary sector e.g. welfare benefits, help with form completion; 
Memory work;
Arts and crafts provided by the voluntary sector; 
Social discussion;
Computer sessions provided by Adult and Community Learning;
Teaching English provided by Adult and Community Learning.

The type of community services the Service Provider shall provide include: 
Volunteer transport to hospital and surgery appointments; 
Transport into Centres for day care and lunches;
Befriending (to reduce isolation, which can lead to depression, self-neglect and residential care);
Group and individual support, in an appropriate and timely manner 
Practical support including form filling, prescription collection, identifying domestic issues and benefit applications.
Support and stimulation to older people, including the elderly frail and vulnerable 
Day opportunities that are flexible, offering stimulation and opportunities for social networking.

The core services for monitoring purposes will include:
Recruitment, training and support of volunteers to ensure the service can offer a flexible and well trained service. This includes a requirement for each of the Leagues to participate in Volunteers Week;
To contribute to activities in relation to Carers Week;
To attend the consultative group meetings for Exeter Co-ordinators;
Transport services - targeted services at achieving of maintaining maximum health and social independence. Examples include escorted access to GP, hospital, dentist, chiropody appointments;
Domiciliary support - services provided in the personÆs home, Examples include escorted shopping, pet care, form filling, and one off maintenance;
Befriending services - services designed to contribute to a reduction in social isolation, loneliness and depression;
Carer support services - services that are as a result of local carer consultation on the Carers Grant allocation. Examples include sitting services, running of a local support group aimed at helping the carer continue in their caring role.
